  "blurb": "A 6,400 m² beachfront estate in quiet East Bali, built in 2023 as a scatter of timber and bamboo pavilions across sand and jungle — a free-form lagoon pool with a rope swing and jump tower, an underground cinema and club, a treetop yoga deck, an open-air gym, infrared sauna and ice bath, and a private bamboo restaurant exclusive to guests. Eight bedrooms, sleeps 21.",
  "detail": "This eight-bedroom estate sits directly on the water in Candidasa, a quiet seaside village on Bali's southeast coast that has kept the unhurried feel the island's busier corners traded away years ago. It spans 6,400 m² and was completed in 2023, and it is less a single house than a small private resort: timber and bamboo pavilions scattered through palms and jungle, linked by sand paths and walkways, with the Indian Ocean at the end of almost every one of them.\n\nThe pool is a free-form lagoon that runs toward the beach, with boulders set into its edge, a rope swing over the water and a jump tower above it. Around the grounds there is a treetop yoga deck, an open-air gym framed by sand and jungle, a beachfront terrace laid with cushions for sunset, and a spa with an infrared sauna and an ice bath set behind glass that looks into the pool. A soundproofed room beneath one of the pavilions works as a cinema, a karaoke room or, if the evening goes that way, a club.\n\nMeals are handled by a private restaurant on the estate, exclusive to guests and built as a soaring bamboo hall with a long timber table and the beach in view. The kitchen leans on local sourcing and cooks both Balinese and international menus. Elsewhere there are several lounges, one framed by a waterfall, and a games room with a pool table, ping pong, a bar and deep leather chesterfields under a psychedelic mural.\n\nThe eight bedrooms are spread across the pavilions rather than stacked in one block, and each is different: two below the cinema, two beside the games room, one in a two-storey treehouse above its own kitchen, one in a pondhouse, and two in a pavilion split by an open-air living area with a glass floor over water. All are air-conditioned and en-suite. One pairs a king bed with an adjoining bunk room that sleeps six, which is how the estate takes 21 guests in total.\n\nThe rate includes daily breakfast, a villa manager, chef, housekeepers, butlers and 24-hour security, with a welcome drink and fruit on arrival. Spa treatments, a car and driver, fishing trips, yacht charter and helicopter tours can all be arranged. Central Candidasa's restaurants are about a kilometre away, the Tirta Gangga water palace roughly thirty minutes, and the hiking trails around Sidemen about forty-five.",
